                "name": "Robert Fishmer",
                "href": "/profile/Robert-Fishmer"
            },
            "answer_text": "A measure is simple yet profound, and you can understand it by adopting the Grand Topological Basis of math.  When one drops the preposterous ideas of sets and set theory, as It's pure haberdash, the necessary ideas behind measure theory of math become clear. Consider the Topology of a point. Now consider the negation of that topology. Take the Cantor Union over all points of all the negated topologies -- this is a measure. Pure and simple. ",
